Introduction

I decided to focus on schools that are from Auckland, is under State authority and are secondary (9-15), I chose to focus on schools that are from Auckland and are secondary (9-15) because I would be most familiar with these schools, I had assumed that schools that are under the same authority would receive the same care when it comes to things like having a liquor store being opened near school grounds, so I wanted the authority to be the same.The robots.txt says to not allow web crawlers to index craft CMS, and also admin was disallowed. The Online terms, privacy and copyright page didn’t say anything about web scraping, only that material on the website being used for commercial purposes have to been given written permission. Based on this information I believe web scraping is allowed.

Visualisation

The main purpose of my visualisation is to see how many liquor stores are near each school.

Creativity

I tried to be creative by seeing if it mattered whether the school went by “School” or “College”, my thought process was that maybe one way sounded more mature and so would’ve made it felt more okay to open up liquor stores near the campus assuming students would go despite them all being in the secondary (9-15) range. I also tried to see if the amount of students in the school had any relation with the amount of liquor stores with the “total” variable. I then colour coded the names with “School”, “College”, or “Other”, and also overlapped the graphs with the student total so it could all be seen together.

Learning Reflection

One idea I learned from this module was the extraction of data from websites. Using code to scrape data from a website is something that I haven’t done before and it was just very interesting to see. Different websites also allowing different levels of access is also interesting to me, especially if they’re the same type of website, like all being school sites but have different policies on the web scraping and what we could use from the site. I’m interested in how to do more with websites and how to extract information from them because it was very cool to see that happen with this module.

reference_schools <- directory_data %>%
  filter(add1_city == "Auckland",
         authority == "State",
         org_type == "Secondary (Year 9-15)") %>%
  select(school_id, org_name, url, latitude, longitude, school_donations, email, authority, co_ed_status, territorial_authority) %>%
  drop_na(url)

write_csv(reference_schools, "reference_schools.csv")

school_ids <- reference_schools$school_id

get_finance <- function(school_id){
  
  page_url <- paste0("https://www.educationcounts.govt.nz/find-school/school/financial-performance?district=&region=&school=", school_id)
  
  Sys.sleep(2)
  
  html <- read_html(page_url) %>%
    html_element("table")
  
  if(length(html) > 0){    
    scraped_data <- html %>%
      html_table() 
    
    financial_data <- scraped_data %>%
      janitor::clean_names() %>%
      mutate(school_operations = parse_number(as.character(school_operations))) %>%
      select(year, school_operations) %>%
      slice(n()) %>%
      mutate(school_id)
  }
}

school_financial_data <- map_df(school_ids, get_finance)

write_csv(school_financial_data, "school_financial_data.csv")

get_html <- function(url){
  
  page <- try(read_html(url), silent = TRUE)
  
  # If no errors
  if (!inherits(page, "try-error")) {
    
    # find any images on page
    images <- page %>%
      html_elements("img") %>%
      html_attr("src")
    
    # count number of images
    num_images_website <- length(images)
    
    return(tibble(url, num_images_website))
  }
}

library(tidyverse)
library(ggplot2)

reference_schools <- read_csv("reference_schools.csv")
school_nearby_liquor_stores <- read_csv("school_nearby_liquor_stores.csv")
school_financial_data <- read_csv("school_financial_data.csv")

school_nearby_liquor_stores <- school_nearby_liquor_stores %>%
  left_join(reference_schools %>%
              select(org_name, latitude, longitude, school_id, total),
            by = c("latitude" = "latitude", "longitude" = "longitude"))

count_by_school <- school_nearby_liquor_stores %>%
  count(school_id, org_name, total, name = "num_liquor_stores") %>%
  mutate(school_or_college = case_when(
    str_detect(org_name, regex("school", ignore_case = TRUE)) ~ "School",
    str_detect(org_name, regex("college", ignore_case = TRUE)) ~ "College",
    TRUE ~ "Other")) #see if the naming of college would mean more liquor stores cause it seems more mature


my_viz <- count_by_school %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_col(aes(x = num_liquor_stores, y = org_name, fill = school_or_college)) + #longer on the x because screen is horizontal and so graph is easier to read
  geom_col(aes(x = total / 1000, y = org_name), fill = "#FFA500", alpha = 0.3) + #make this transparent so the other bars can be seen
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("School" = "#4cc9f0", "College" = "#008000", "Other" = "#800080")) + #colours picked so overlap with orange is easy to see
  labs(title = "Number of Liquor Stores nearby for each School",
       subtitle = "Schools are from Auckland with State authority and is Secondary (9-15)",
       x = "Amount of Liquor Stores nearby",
       y = "School Name",
       caption = "Orange bar = Amount of Students (In Thousands)")


ggsave("my_viz.png", plot = my_viz, width = 10, height = 6, units = "in")
